Image Ikin Yum.

tsunagu londontheatre artlondon artmag https://t.co/acatn1p7rw
Title: Island Mentalities: The Women Bridging Britain And Japan At Tsunagu/Connect | Artmag | All The Arts In Scotland
Description: Tsunagu bridges Britain and Japan by storytelling . Co-creators Kumiko Mendl and Kazuko Hohki lead an impressively-credited crew composed almost entirely of women . Vignettes range from Showa-era Japan to bedsits of 1980s London .  Japanese women are doubly bound by stereotypes of gender and race, both at home and abroad . Tsunagu centres on these contemporary experiences of dislocation . Japan’s strict citizenship requirements today reinforce such binaries . Dual nationality is permitted only for young people under 22 .

tweet: Unaligned Supervision for Automatic Music Transcription in The Wild : https://t.co/g7yiY39b5U Multi-instrument Automatic Music Transcription (AMT) or the decoding of a musical recording into semantic musical content, is one of the holy grails of Music Information Retrieval. https://t.co/hoFWJCKxOG
Title: Unaligned Supervision for Automatic Music Transcription in The Wild.
Description: Multi-instrument Automatic Music Transcription (AMT) is one of the holy grails of Music Information Retrieval . Current AMT approaches are restricted to piano and (some) guitar recordings . We introduce NoteEM, a method for simultaneously training a transcriber and align  The labels are in the form of MIDI files aligned with the audio, and include instrument information . Onset timing accuracy of the labels is 32ms, which is sufficient to train a transcriber .

Description: In the depths of the British Library Sound Archive lies a wonderful treasure trove of illicit audio recordings . Such bootlegs are rock’n’roll relics of the pre-Internet age, perhaps only valued now by collectors . The audio they contain, once highly prized and difficult  'Trade Mark of Quality' (TMQ) label began to pump out a steady stream of concert recordings by the big rock bands of the era . TMQ’s ‘Live'r Than You'll Ever Be’ is said to have sold over 250,000  All of the big British artists of the day were bootlegged – often by outfits based abroad like TMQ . Records would be pressed abroad because the legal consequences were less significant . But, with the coming of punk, a homegrown bootleg culture really got going in the UK .  Bootlegs of forbidden music cut onto X-ray film in Cold War era Soviet Union . The CBMR holds 47,000 sound recordings in all formats; over 100 individual archival collections over 15,000 scores, images,  The CBMR library was the only special collection like it at the time of its foundation . The space itself was drab and not at all inviting, but the weight of knowledge that occupied its shelves drew me in . I felt a sense of power and pride as I read about the  In July 2019, the Columbia College Archives and Special Collections office moved all of the library books to the back room, making them no longer visible to visitors . The experience of discovering new knowledge that felt so intrinsic to accessing the library was lost .  The CBMR collections were removed from Columbia College library after the COVID-19 pandemic . The public had no access to the very space that became something of a sanctuary for me during my undergraduate years . I envisioned the CBMR expanding into a community space, a gallery space,  In July 2019, the Columbia Chronicle reported that due to staffing challenges at the college, Laurie and Janet were terminated from the CBMR and Melanie resigned . With this news came confusion about what would happen to the collection . Currently, only researchers are allowed to schedule appointments with the main library  Thousands upon thousands of photos, documents, books, music, and artifacts that tell stories of the lives, brilliance, and work of Black folks are behind walls, in closets, and on shelves, collecting dust . Title: Music for a Revolution | The Tyee
Description: A new documentary portrait of Venezuelan conductor Gustavo Dudamel, ¡Viva Maestro! , packs in the biggest musical themes . Director Theodore Braun started his film in 2017, just as Dudamel was preparing for a European tour of Beethoven's symphonies .  The film stars Venezuelan conductor and conductor as Venezuela descends into economic and social chaos . The real drama of the documentary kicks in as the violence spirals out of control of the government . The violent street protests against the government resulted in multiple injuries and death .  The idea that music could in fact change society was a critical part of El Sistema, the program for kids of all backgrounds founded by José Antonio Abreu . The idea finds voice in the quietest moments of ¡Viva Maestro! .
